---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="MCP: Connect Claude Code to External Tools"
  description="From basic setup to advanced Notion integration — learn how to use MCP to connect Claude Code to databases, design tools, document tools, and other APIs."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container cc-mcp">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Connect Claude Code to Tools, Teach It New Tricks, and Automate Repetitive Work</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          We've already set up the basics for Claude Code — CLAUDE.md, memory management, context handling.
          The next stage isn't about stuffing more rules into the handbook. It's about giving Claude Code
          new abilities. Some let it see external tools, some let it follow fixed workflows, some let it
          farm out large tasks, and some automate repetitive actions. These abilities each have their own role.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Section 1: What is MCP -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">MCP: Connecting Claude Code to External Tools</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        MCP connects Claude Code to external services — databases, design tools, document tools,
        monitoring tools, even other APIs. Once set up, Claude Code can go beyond "reading what you
        paste in" and actually reach into those systems to read data or use their tools directly.
      </p>

      <div class="info-card">
        <p class="info-title">Plain-language analogy</p>
        <p class="info-body">
          MCP is like a USB cable. Claude Code is the computer, and the external service is a
          peripheral. Plug them together and Claude Code can operate that device directly.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 2: Common commands -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Common Commands</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Run these three commands in the VS Code integrated terminal:
      </p>

      <div class="cmd-list">
        <article class="cmd-card">
          <div class="cmd-head">
            <span class="cmd-num">1</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="cmd-title">claude mcp add &lt;args&gt;</h3>
              <p class="cmd-alias">Add an MCP server</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="cmd-card">
          <div class="cmd-head">
            <span class="cmd-num">2</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="cmd-title">claude mcp get &lt;server-name&gt;</h3>
              <p class="cmd-alias">Check the status of a specific MCP server</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="cmd-card">
          <div class="cmd-head">
            <span class="cmd-num">3</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="cmd-title">claude mcp list</h3>
              <p class="cmd-alias">List all configured MCP servers</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 3: Basic setup tutorial (collapsible) -->
      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary class="collapsible-trigger">
          <span class="collapsible-icon"></span>
          <span class="collapsible-title">MCP Basic Setup & Test Tutorial</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="collapsible-body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            If you're using VS Code on Windows, the most reliable approach is to use <strong>project scope</strong>.
          </p>

          <div class="tip-card">
            <p class="tip-title">Why project scope?</p>
            <ul class="tip-list">
              <li>Project scope writes MCP settings to <code>.mcp.json</code> in your project root — easy to inspect.</li>
              <li>The official docs state: project-scoped MCP servers live in <code>.mcp.json</code>, while
                user and local scopes are stored in <code>~/.claude.json</code>.
                On Windows, the VS Code extension may read the project path with a lowercase <code>c:/...</code>,
                while the CLI writes uppercase <code>C:/...</code> into <code>~/.claude.json</code>,
                causing the extension to miss the config.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <ol class="step-list">
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">1</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Open a folder in VS Code</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Create and open a new folder, e.g. <code>test-basic-mcp</code>. This will be the project root for this test.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">2</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Verify your environment</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Many local MCP servers run on Node.js, so make sure it works. In the VS Code integrated terminal:
                </p>
                <pre class="code-block"><code>claude --version
node --version</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">If both show version numbers, you're good to go.</p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">3</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Create .mcp.json</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Create <code>.mcp.json</code> in your project root with this content:
                </p>
                <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`{
  "mcpServers": {
    "everything-test": {
      "type": "stdio",
      "command": "cmd",
      "args": ["/c", "npx", "-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-everything"]
    }
  }
}`} /></pre>
                <div class="note-card">
                  <p class="note-body">
                    <strong>everything-test</strong> is the name you give this MCP server.
                    On Windows, the official docs recommend wrapping npx with <code>cmd /c</code>.
                    <strong>stdio</strong> means Claude Code launches the server as a child process and
                    communicates via standard I/O — this is one of MCP's standard local transports.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">4</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Create .claude/settings.local.json</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Create <code>.claude/settings.local.json</code> in the project root:
                </p>
                <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`{
  "enabledMcpjsonServers": ["everything-test"]
}`} /></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  This is important: project-scoped MCP servers require approval.
                  <code>enabledMcpjsonServers</code> approves specific servers from <code>.mcp.json</code>.
                </p>
                <div class="note-card">
                  <p class="note-body">
                    Shortcut: you can use <code set:html={`{ "enableAllProjectMcpServers": true }`} /> instead
                    to auto-approve all MCP servers in <code>.mcp.json</code>.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">5</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Reload the VS Code window</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Press <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Shift</kbd>+<kbd>P</kbd>, type
                  <code>Developer: Reload Window</code>, and press Enter.
                  This lets the VS Code extension pick up your new config files.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">6</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">"See tools" test</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">In the Claude Code chat box, type:</p>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>List the available tools from the everything-test MCP server.</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  If Claude Code lists the tools, the MCP server has been loaded successfully.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">7</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">"Call a tool" test</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">In the Claude Code chat box, type:</p>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>Use everything-test to run the simplest MCP test and show me the result.</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  If Claude Code calls a tool and returns a result, your MCP is fully connected.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Section 4: Advanced tutorial — Notion (collapsible) -->
      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary class="collapsible-trigger">
          <span class="collapsible-icon"></span>
          <span class="collapsible-title">Advanced Tutorial: Connect Claude Code to Notion</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="collapsible-body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            If the everything-test above taught you "how MCP connects," this section teaches you
            "what MCP can actually do." Notion is a great demo because it's commonly used for notes,
            project planning, to-dos, and meeting notes. Once connected, Claude Code can search
            Notion pages, organize content, draft for you, and even update pages.
          </p>

          <div class="compare-grid">
            <div class="compare-card">
              <p class="compare-label">Previous: Basic tutorial</p>
              <p class="compare-title">Local stdio server</p>
              <p class="compare-desc">Tests whether the MCP mechanism works at all.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-card compare-card--accent">
              <p class="compare-label">This section: Advanced tutorial</p>
              <p class="compare-title">Remote HTTP server</p>
              <p class="compare-desc">Official Notion MCP endpoint with OAuth authorization.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="tip-card">
            <p class="tip-title">Before you start</p>
            <ul class="tip-list">
              <li>A Notion account with at least one page accessible</li>
              <li>Claude Code working normally</li>
              <li>A fresh test folder, e.g. <code>test-notion-mcp</code></li>
              <li>Confirm <code>claude --version</code> and <code>node --version</code></li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <ol class="step-list">
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">1</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Add Notion MCP to your project</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">In the VS Code integrated terminal:</p>
                <pre class="code-block"><code>claude mcp add --transport http notion --scope project https://mcp.notion.com/mcp</code></pre>
                <div class="note-card">
                  <p class="note-body">
                    This command does three things at once:
                    <strong>--transport http</strong> means a remote HTTP MCP server;
                    <strong>notion</strong> is the server name;
                    <strong>--scope project</strong> writes the config to <code>.mcp.json</code>.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">2</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Confirm .mcp.json exists</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Open the VS Code file explorer and confirm <code>.mcp.json</code> has appeared in your project root.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">3</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Reload the VS Code window</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Press <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Shift</kbd>+<kbd>P</kbd>, type
                  <code>Developer: Reload Window</code>, and press Enter.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">4</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Complete authorization in Claude Code</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  In the Claude Code chat box, type <code>/mcp</code>, select MCP servers,
                  find the notion server, and complete OAuth login as prompted.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">5</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">"See tools" test</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">In the Claude Code chat box, type:</p>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>List the available tools from the notion MCP server.</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Don't rush into doing things — first verify that Claude can actually see the tools.
                  If it lists Notion-related tools, the MCP server has been loaded.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">6</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">"Read data" test</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Start with reading — it's safer. In the Claude Code chat box:</p>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>Show me the titles of recently accessible pages in my Notion workspace.</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  If successful, Claude will actually fetch data from Notion instead of asking you to
                  paste content. The earlier "list tools" test only proves it can see the tools;
                  this step proves it can actually reach your Notion workspace.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">7</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Real test: create a new page</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Once reading succeeds, try the most tangible test:</p>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>Create a new page in my Notion titled "MCP Test Note".
Content:
1. This page was created by Claude Code via Notion MCP
2. The purpose of this test is to confirm the MCP connection is working
3. If you can see this page, authorization and tool calls both succeeded</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  If successful, a new note will actually appear in Notion.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Section 5: Common issues (collapsible) -->
      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary class="collapsible-trigger">
          <span class="collapsible-icon"></span>
          <span class="collapsible-title">Common Issues & Solutions</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="collapsible-body">
          <div class="faq-list">
            <article class="faq-card">
              <h3 class="faq-q">claude mcp list shows "No MCP servers configured," but claude mcp get everything-test shows Connected</h3>
              <p class="faq-a">
                This doesn't necessarily mean your MCP isn't working.
              </p>
              <div class="faq-solution">
                <p class="faq-solution-label">Solution</p>
                <ul class="faq-solution-list">
                  <li>Trust the result from <code>claude mcp get everything-test</code></li>
                  <li>Go straight to the chat box and run a real test</li>
                  <li>Don't rely solely on <code>list</code> to determine success</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </article>

            <article class="faq-card">
              <h3 class="faq-q">Claude Code says the server is installed, but tools don't appear in the available tools list</h3>
              <p class="faq-a">
                Possible causes: <code>.mcp.json</code> exists but the session hasn't reloaded;
                the project MCP hasn't been approved; you're still in an old conversation.
              </p>
              <div class="faq-solution">
                <p class="faq-solution-label">Solution</p>
                <ul class="faq-solution-list">
                  <li>Confirm <code>.claude/settings.local.json</code> has the correct approval setting</li>
                  <li>Reload the VS Code window (<kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Shift</kbd>+<kbd>P</kbd> → Developer: Reload Window)</li>
                  <li>Start a new conversation</li>
                  <li>Ask Claude: "List the available tools from everything-test"</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Summary -->
      <div class="summary-card">
        <p class="summary-title">Key takeaways</p>
        <ul class="summary-list">
          <li><strong>MCP</strong> — the bridge that connects Claude Code to external services. Once set up, it can operate external tools directly.</li>
          <li><strong>stdio</strong> — the standard connection method for local MCP servers, ideal for testing and dev tools.</li>
          <li><strong>HTTP + OAuth</strong> — the connection method for remote cloud services like Notion, Gmail, etc.</li>
          <li><strong>project scope</strong> — the most reliable MCP config approach on Windows + VS Code.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .cc-mcp {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Header */
  .detail-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-title {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .detail-subtitle {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  /* Section headings */
  .detail-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-paragraph {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .detail-paragraph strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* ── Collapsible sections ── */
  .collapsible {
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-left: 4px solid #8b5cf6;
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    overflow: hidden;
    transition: border-color var(--transition);
  }

  .collapsible[open] {
    border-top-color: #8b5cf6;
    border-right-color: #8b5cf6;
    border-bottom-color: #8b5cf6;
  }

  .collapsible-trigger {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    width: 100%;
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    user-select: none;
    transition: background-color var(--transition);
  }

  .collapsible-trigger::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .collapsible-trigger:hover {
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
  }

  .collapsible-icon {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 1.25rem;
    height: 1.25rem;
    position: relative;
    transition: transform 0.2s ease;
  }

  .collapsible-icon::before,
  .collapsible-icon::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    background-color: #8b5cf6;
    border-radius: 1px;
  }

  .collapsible-icon::before {
    top: 50%;
    left: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 2px;
    transform: translateY(-50%);
  }

  .collapsible-icon::after {
    top: 0;
    left: 50%;
    width: 2px;
    height: 100%;
    transform: translateX(-50%);
    transition: opacity 0.2s ease;
  }

  .collapsible[open] .collapsible-icon::after {
    opacity: 0;
  }

  .collapsible-title {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
  }

  .collapsible-body {
    padding: var(--space-6);
  }

  /* ── Info card ── */
  .info-card {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .info-title {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .info-body {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 500;
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* ── Command cards ── */
  .cmd-list {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .cmd-card {
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    transition: all var(--transition);
  }

  .cmd-card:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .cmd-head {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-4);
  }

  .cmd-num {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 2rem;
    height: 2rem;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background-color: var(--color-accent);
    color: #fff;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .cmd-title {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
  }

  .cmd-alias {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  /* ── Step list (tutorial steps) ── */
  .step-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-6) 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-6);
  }

  .step-item {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    align-items: flex-start;
  }

  .step-num {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 2rem;
    height: 2rem;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background-color: var(--color-accent);
    color: #fff;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-top: 0.15rem;
  }

  .step-body {
    flex: 1;
    min-width: 0;
  }

  .step-title {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .step-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .step-desc:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  /* ── Code blocks ── */
  .code-block {
    margin: var(--space-3) 0 var(--space-4);
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--color-text);
    overflow-x: auto;
    white-space: pre;
  }

  .code-block code {
    font-family: inherit;
    background: none;
    padding: 0;
    color: inherit;
  }

  .code-block--command {
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 600;
    white-space: pre-wrap;
  }

  /* ── Tip card ── */
  .tip-card {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
  }

  .tip-title {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 700;
